Raw dev notes -- Migration Mayhem and Model Musings

Okay, so this past week has been a whirlwind on the Weaverai_Agents_MCP project. This thing is essentially our central brain for all AI agent operations – it's where we orchestrate complex workflows, manage various LLMs, and build out custom skills for our agents. The *huge* underlying theme for this period was a massive migration effort, moving everything from our legacy setup to a new, dedicated AI platform.

What we actually got done feels like a mountain. The biggest chunk was definitely the **migration itself**. We finally completed the full switch over to the new platform, which involved a ton of work migrating existing n8n and Flowise workflows. That meant updating our `.env.example` files to support both the old and new deployment targets, making sure everything was clearly labeled. Post-migration, there was a lot of hygiene work: wiring Open-WebUI to LiteLLM, updating our DevOps delta docs, and just generally tidying up.

Beyond the migration, I spent a good chunk of time shoring up our **infrastructure and deployment tooling**. I added multi-namespace dumping to `headlamp` for better auditing, and improved `setup_fresh_pod` to do a pre-flight check for Chroma DB before waiting on health endpoints – learned that the hard way, services don't always come up in the order you expect! Fixed a small but annoying bug in `restore_chroma` where it wouldn't create the parent directory before `mktemp`. Also, made our `start_services` scripts smarter: they now loudly detect Python versions below 3.12 and surface `pip install` failures, which has saved me some headaches. And finally, cleaned up some legacy cruft by dropping the old `/tmp/hf_eph` symlink and using the PVC HF cache directly, including a robust `rm -rf` for any lingering legacy directories.

On the **LLM and agent skills** front, we added a new `garage-s3-helper` skill, which is pretty cool. I also refined our `promptfoo` skills, merging `ui-map` into `promptfoo-expert` and adding comprehensive documentation. There were some tricky fixes for `litellm-langfuse` wiring – found two silent-fail gotchas that were a pain to track down. We also did a bunch of work around **model management**: downloading Llama-3.3, setting up a model bake-off playbook, and fixing a critical config issue for 70B AWQ presets that needed `gpu_count=2` and `--tensor-parallel-size 2`.

**Documentation** got some love too, with updates to our `devops delta` regarding in-cluster Service DNS rules versus public endpoints, and a new `Devops doc` covering SMB CSI gaps and storage state.

The **hardest part** was definitely the migration. It's never just a flip of a switch; there are always subtle differences in environment, networking, and service discovery that bite you. Those "silent-fail gotchas" in `litellm-langfuse` were particularly frustrating – you think everything's working, but data isn't flowing correctly. And the GPU configuration for the 70B models? That was a classic "why isn't this working?!" moment until I realized the specific `gpu_count` and `tensor-parallel-size` were critical. It's a constant reminder that even small details can derail a complex system. Dealing with legacy `tmp` directories and symlinks also felt like digital archaeology.

**Personally**, getting this migration done feels like a huge weight off my shoulders. It was a big, complex lift, and seeing everything finally running on the new platform is incredibly satisfying. It reinforced the importance of robust pre-flight checks and clear documentation, especially when dealing with multiple environments. I also got a much deeper understanding of the nuances of deploying large language models and managing their dependencies. It's a constant learning curve, and sometimes it feels like I'm just patching holes, but then you get a big win like this migration, and it feels pretty good.

Next up: Diving deeper into corpus translation capabilities.
